lass=\"wp-block-heading\">Let\'s get acquainted so I can figure out how I can begin to help you. </h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please take the first challenge to tell me about yourself.  Once we get acquainted I can learn about your needs and desires and continue to develop this site to help you move forward.   I can also get some feedback from you on what is helpful and what is not so much.  Eventually, I would like you to consider being more actively involved in making this site a place where you can help others and learn from them too. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-yourself-so-i-know-how-i-can-help-you/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"181\">Take the challenge of introducing your self.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Let\'s consider your development environment</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are reading this you are probably far enough into web development that you have at least a starter machine and programs to get the work done.    I have a summary of development platforms that you should read to consider what you have, what you might need to move forward.   At the end of that I\'d like to know what you have and what you think you might need.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/development-platforms/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"175\">Learn more about development platforms..</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Take a challenge to <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-your-development-setup/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"184\">tell me about your current development setup...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Finding work as an individual</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a number of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freelancer\">freelance</a> marketplaces online.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.upwork.com/freelance-jobs/\">Upwork</a> is one we recommend.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/finding-work/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"79\">Learn more about freelancing work...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Working as part of a team</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because of the rapid pace of technology development and market requirements, most web and application development is done by integrated teams.  No one person can do it all themselves. It takes a team of specialists working individually and cross discipline to be successful. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A team can take on big jobs that a single person cannot do.   This presents opportunity for the individual developer.  Once you understand how a team can work together you can find the best place to contribute.   But while you are doing what you already know how to do, you will also learn something about the rest of the team and the roles they fill.   And you will find avenues to learn new skills while you build team skills.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/working-in-a-professional-team/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"149\">Learn more about working as part of a larger team ...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Development platforms</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Doing web development work as an individual can be done with most any computer running Windows, Linux, or Macintosh.   You most likely already made a choice and are doing work.   However, as you move into full stack work, or start working as part of a team it will get more complex.   It is worth considering the options again. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, take a moment to<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/development-platforms/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"175\"> learn more about development platforms...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Accepting challenges to put your learning to work.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You may have already encountered a prompt to accept a challenge as you have read this far.  If so, good for you.   I will continue to add more challenges to keep you moving forward.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Learn more from the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">complete list of challenges...</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">How to do many things related to this work</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I continue to develop <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"108\">how to pages on simple and more advanced topics.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Latest Posts</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:latest-posts {\"align\":\"center\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Home','','inherit','closed','closed','','2-revision-v1','','','2024-02-16 16:39:12','2024-02-16 16:39:12','',2,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=217',0,'revision','',0),(219,1,'2024-02-16 16:49:03','2024-02-16 16:49:03','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Front end, or<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Front-end_web_development\"> front-end web development</a> refers to the skills and technology related to building pages and applications that run in a web browser.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Skills</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a number of skills to learn in order to be a typical web designer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Almost all of them can be learned at a number of mentor sites.  One of which is <a href=\"https://www.frontendmentor.io\">FrontendMentor</a>.  That site (and others like it) have a wealth of information and tutorials that teach you the fundamentals and details of all of these skills.   After reading this page and exploring FrontendMentor some, I recommend you try one of their challenges yourself.     </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Looking ahead, in our page on <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally…</a> there is a challenge to do one of the FrontendMentor challenges and capture your process and final work in a GitHub repository that you can show off what you have learned.   Keep an eye out for that, as it is a very important step in your professional development. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML - Hyper Text Markup Language</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML\">HTML</a> is a rich markup language which can be viewed and coded in a simple text editing program.   It consists of the text to be presented interspersed with HTML markup tags that specify how that text should be displayed.   The filename usually ends in either .htm or .html to indicated that it can be displayed in a web browser.  The HTML markup standards have been around since the beginning of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web\">World Wide Web.</a>  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML5</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML5\">HTML5</a> is simply the 5th major revision of the HTML standards that added significant modern features that make some web pages very dynamic. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">CSS - Cascading Style Sheets</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CSS\">CSS</a> is a speciality language for styling text and graphics.   While simple HTML can be coded to create the desired look and layout it can be extremely tedious to do so on a large scale.   If you are not consistent then the look and feel will be inconsistent.  Furthermore, if you decide to change the way your site looks then you will have a monstrous job to adjust all of the tags from start to finish.   The intent of CSS is that the raw HTML page should contain the content only.   A single reference in the header of the page is made to a .css file that contains the styling directives.   If you choose to change the look and feel, then you can code a new css file and change the reference to point to the new one.    A further refinement of that idea is with a content management system (CMS) that stores the content in a database.  But, that is another subject for another day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">JavaScript - A procedural programming language for web pages.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Javascript\">JavaScript</a> is a programming language inspired by Java that is meant to run inside a web page.   All of the actual work is performed by the web browser itself. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As discussed above, all of the above technologies can run on any computer with a web browser.  The HTML, CSS files and any embedded JavaScript code can be contained in a text file in a folder on the local computer.   You can test this yourself by creating a simple web page in a text editor (Notepad or TextEdit) and storing it on your hard drive.  Cut and paste this in your favorite text editor into a file called HelloWorld.htm:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;HTML&gt;\n&lt;H1&gt;Hello World!&lt;/H1&gt;\n&lt;/HTML&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then using your file browser (Windows explorer or Mac Finder) to locate that file and open it as you would any other document. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTTP - Hypertext Transport Protocol</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes, that is all that is needed.  However, that does not make any use of the internet or the World Wide Web.   The \"World Wide\" part of the Web indicates that computers all over the world that are connected to the internet can work together to present a very dynamic universe of information and entertainment.    In order to connect your local computer to any web page in the World Wide Web you simply enter a web address such as <a href=\"http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm\">http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm</a> into the search or address bar of your browser.   The first four characters stand for HyperText Transport Protocol.  After that the \':\' indicates the beginning of the location of the resource which usually starts with \'//\' followed by the name of the resource.   Try it yourself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What happened when you pressed return after that address is that your browser used that resource information to find the appropriate web server somewhere in the world (MichaelKentBurns.com) and request a specific page (HelloWorld.htm).  A program called a web server running on that computer located the file for that page and other associated information and sent it back to your browser running on your computer.  Your browser then formatted it according to the HTML rules and you then see the results.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The details of that is for the next page (<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/back-end-web/\">Back end web</a>).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Front end web','','inherit','closed','closed','','49-revision-v1','','','2024-02-16 16:49:03','2024-02-16 16:49:03','',49,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=219',0,'revision','',0),(220,1,'2024-02-16 16:51:24','2024-02-16 16:51:24','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Front end, or<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Front-end_web_development\"> front-end web development</a> refers to the skills and technology related to building pages and applications that run in a web browser.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Skills</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a number of skills to learn in order to be a typical web designer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Almost all of them can be learned at a number of mentor sites.  One of which is <a href=\"https://www.frontendmentor.io\">FrontendMentor</a>.  That site (and others like it) have a wealth of information and tutorials that teach you the fundamentals and details of all of these skills.   After reading this page and exploring FrontendMentor some, I recommend you try one of their challenges yourself.     </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Looking ahead, in our page on <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/work-globally/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"59\">Work globally…</a> there is a challenge to do one of the FrontendMentor challenges and capture your process and final work in a GitHub repository that you can show off what you have learned.   Keep an eye out for that, as it is a very important step in your professional development. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML - Hyper Text Markup Language</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML\">HTML</a> is a rich markup language which can be viewed and coded in a simple text editing program.   It consists of the text to be presented interspersed with HTML markup tags that specify how that text should be displayed.   The filename usually ends in either .htm or .html to indicated that it can be displayed in a web browser.  The HTML markup standards have been around since the beginning of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web\">World Wide Web.</a>  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTML5</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML5\">HTML5</a> is simply the 5th major revision of the HTML standards that added significant modern features that make some web pages very dynamic. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">CSS - Cascading Style Sheets</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CSS\">CSS</a> is a speciality language for styling text and graphics.   While simple HTML can be coded to create the desired look and layout it can be extremely tedious to do so on a large scale.   If you are not consistent then the look and feel will be inconsistent.  Furthermore, if you decide to change the way your site looks then you will have a monstrous job to adjust all of the tags from start to finish.   The intent of CSS is that the raw HTML page should contain the content only.   A single reference in the header of the page is made to a .css file that contains the styling directives.   If you choose to change the look and feel, then you can code a new css file and change the reference to point to the new one.    A further refinement of that idea is with a content management system (CMS) that stores the content in a database.  But, that is another subject for another day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">JavaScript - A procedural programming language for web pages.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Javascript\">JavaScript</a> is a programming language inspired by Java that is meant to run inside a web page.   All of the actual work is performed by the web browser itself. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As discussed above, all of the above technologies can run on any computer with a web browser.  The HTML, CSS files and any embedded JavaScript code can be contained in a text file in a folder on the local computer.   You can test this yourself by creating a simple web page in a text editor (Notepad or TextEdit) and storing it on your hard drive.  Cut and paste this in your favorite text editor into a file called HelloWorld.htm:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;HTML&gt;\n&lt;H1&gt;Hello World!&lt;/H1&gt;\n&lt;/HTML&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then using your file browser (Windows explorer or Mac Finder) to locate that file and open it as you would any other document. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">HTTP - Hypertext Transport Protocol</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes, that is all that is needed.  However, that does not make any use of the internet or the World Wide Web.   The \"World Wide\" part of the Web indicates that computers all over the world that are connected to the internet can work together to present a very dynamic universe of information and entertainment.    In order to connect your local computer to any web page in the World Wide Web you simply enter a web address such as <a href=\"http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm\">http://MichaelKentBurns.com/HelloWorld.htm</a> into the search or address bar of your browser.   The first four characters stand for HyperText Transport Protocol.  After that the \':\' indicates the beginning of the location of the resource which usually starts with \'//\' followed by the name of the resource.   Try it yourself.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What happened when you pressed return after that address is that your browser used that resource information to find the appropriate web server somewhere in the world (MichaelKentBurns.com) and request a specific page (HelloWorld.htm).  A web server program running on that computer located the file for that page and other associated information and sent it back to your browser running on your computer.  Your browser then formatted it according to the HTML rules and you then see the results.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The details of that is for the next page (<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/back-end-web/\">Back end web</a>).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Front end web','','inherit','closed','closed','','49-revision-v1','','','2024-02-16 16:51:24','2024-02-16 16:51:24','',49,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=220',0,'revision','',0),(221,1,'2024-02-16 17:10:14','2024-02-16 17:10:14','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">GitHub</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the advent of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open-source_software\"><strong>open-source software</strong></a> there arose the need to have world wide access to the source code for the many projects.   <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git\"><strong>Git</strong></a> is the source control tool invented for Linux development, but it is now widely used on all platforms, operating systems, and languages.    I actually use Git to control the source of this entire WordPress site. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are command line versions of git for all major desktop systems.  One of the more popular graphical interfaces for git is <a href=\"https://desktop.github.com\"><strong>GitDesktop</strong></a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GitHub\"><strong>GitHub</strong></a> is a web interface for software development which uses Git for the source control features, and describes itself as collaborative version control.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>GitHub</strong> supports the creation of personal accounts.  Each account can contain a number of repositories, which can be made public or private access.   A personal account allows a developer to create a repository for each project that is being worked on.   On the developer\'s personal machine, a matching copy of the GitHub repository can be made in a process called cloning.   As work progresses on the local machine and certain testable milestones are reached, the local changes can be committed and pushed to the GitHub repository.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get an idea of how this looks visit <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\">my GitHub account.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using a GitHub account with repositories for each project that you have done allows others (if your repo is public) to see not only your code and documentation, but also the process you used to make the changes.   Each time you fix a bug or add a new feature, you should push that to GitHub with a comment that describes the fix or new feature.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With all that in mind you should take action now by taking my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-setup-your-own-github-account-and-install-desktop-github-app/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"187\">Challenge: Setup your own GitHub account and install Desktop GitHub app</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Capture your learning in a repository.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many tutorial sites to help you learn new skills.  As an example look at <strong><a href=\"https://www.frontendmentor.io\">Frontend Mentor.</a></strong>  It is a good practice to capture your work for each challenge in a GitHub repository.  While it seems natural to download the starting material and jump right into the work, resist this urge and be very intentional about utilizing the features of Git.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you begin a challenge, you should create a GitHub repository and do all of your work step by step capturing your work as you go.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you are ready to try that, go to<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-capture-a-tutorial-project-in-a-github-repository/\"> the challenge page</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you are all finished with the challenge, take the time to update the ReadMe file in the repository.   In the first paragraph, and prominently marked, describe the specific skills demonstrated.  For instance if you are learning new HTML5 multimedia tags, list those.   This will be important when you start looking for work.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, update your resumé, CV, or Upwork profile to have a link to that repository.  A prospect client reading your profile will be able to click on that and see a clear demonstration that you actually do know that specific skill.    One final note is that when you do a real project of your own design,  replace the link to the challenge repository with a link to your own original project repository.   Putting your skills to work on a project of your own design shows that you really know how and why to use that skill.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Create a project with other developers.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you learn with your friends take the opportunity to propose an original project that you all can work on together.   Get a consensus of the scope and focus of the project, but feel free to include some features that require a skill that only a few collaborators know well.   This teaches the real world reality that open-source software is a collaboration of many people to build and enhance projects that no single person can achieve alone. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Search GitHub for a project that you are interested in learning more about it. </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Take some time to browse the galaxy of open-source projects in GitHub and find ones that you know about, or are interested in learning about.   You can actively follow the work of others, and can review the code that has been pushed to see how it has been coded.    Clone the repository to your local machine so you have a working copy.  As you test it out and find bugs or desired features, consider creating an issue in the GitHub project.   Note that some repositories have restrictions about who can do what.   By following projects, you will learn.  As you submit features, and if you get a chance to fix an issue you will start building your public credentials.   When you do that, be sure to update your resumé or CV or profile to point the projects you have participated in.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Work globally','','inherit','closed','closed','','59-autosave-v1','','','2024-02-16 17:10:14','2024-02-16 17:10:14','',59,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=221',0,'revision','',0),(222,1,'2024-02-16 17:08:57','2024-02-16 17:08:57','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your task is to create a new repository for doing a tutorial project (of your choosing) and capturing your work step by step in that repository.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Don\'t forget to <a href=\"mailto: MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">send me an email</a> (following the instructions on the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">Challenges page</a>) with a link to your new repository, a writeup of what you learned, and what problems or questions you had.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have already done that myself using a simple FrontEndMentor challenge.   I captured the whole process in a file called Notes.md in that repository.  Find the link to my repository below.  So, go to my repository and locate the Notes.md file.   You can look around in my repository to see the code I downloaded, the tasks that I decided I needed (called Issues in GitHub terms) and the step by step work to the completed project.   I also used GitHub Pages to publish the end result for the world to see.  Make sure you do the same for your new project. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is my project repository:   <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component/\">https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Challenge: capture a tutorial project in a GitHub repository','','publish','closed','closed','','challenge-capture-a-tutorial-project-in-a-github-repository','','','2024-03-09 13:26:36','2024-03-09 13:26:36','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=222',0,'page','',0),(224,1,'2024-02-16 17:08:57','2024-02-16 17:08:57','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your task is to create a new repository for doing a tutorial project (of your choosing) and capturing your work step by step in that repository.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I have already done that myself using a simple FrontEndMentor challenge.   I captured the whole process in a file called Notes.md in that repository.  So, go to my repository and locate the Notes.md file.   You can look around in my repository to see the code I downloaded, the tasks that I decided I needed (called Issues in GitHub terms) and the step by step work to the completed project.   I also used GitHub Pages to publish the end result for the world to see.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is my project repository:   <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component/\">https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns/Challenge-Interactive-rating-component/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After you have looked at mine, do your own.   When you are done <a href=\"mailto: MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">send me an email</a> with that link and a writeup of what you learned, what problems or questions you had.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Challenge: capture a tutorial project in a GitHub repository','','inherit','closed','closed','','222-revision-v1','','','2024-02-16 17:08:57','2024-02-16 17:08:57','',222,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=224',0,'revision','',0),(225,1,'2024-02-16 17:10:47','2024-02-16 17:10:47','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">GitHub</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With the advent of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open-source_software\"><strong>open-source software</strong></a> there arose the need to have world wide access to the source code for the many projects.   <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git\"><strong>Git</strong></a> is the source control tool invented for Linux development, but it is now widely used on all platforms, operating systems, and languages.    I actually use Git to control the source of this entire WordPress site. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are command line versions of git for all major desktop systems.  One of the more popular graphical interfaces for git is <a href=\"https://desktop.github.com\"><strong>GitDesktop</strong></a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GitHub\"><strong>GitHub</strong></a> is a web interface for software development which uses Git for the source control features, and describes itself as collaborative version control.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>GitHub</strong> supports the creation of personal accounts.  Each account can contain a number of repositories, which can be made public or private access.   A personal account allows a developer to create a repository for each project that is being worked on.   On the developer\'s personal machine, a matching copy of the GitHub repository can be made in a process called cloning.   As work progresses on the local machine and certain testable milestones are reached, the local changes can be committed and pushed to the GitHub repository.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get an idea of how this looks visit <a href=\"https://github.com/MichaelKentBurns\">my GitHub account.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using a GitHub account with repositories for each project that you have done allows others (if your repo is public) to see not only your code and documentation, but also the process you used to make the changes.   Each time you fix a bug or add a new feature, you should push that to GitHub with a comment that describes the fix or new feature.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With all that in mind you should take action now by taking my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-setup-your-own-github-account-and-install-desktop-github-app/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"187\">Challenge: Setup your own GitHub account and install Desktop GitHub app</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Capture your learning in a repository.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are many tutorial sites to help you learn new skills.  As an example look at <strong><a href=\"https://www.frontendmentor.io\">Frontend Mentor.</a></strong>  It is a good practice to capture your work for each challenge in a GitHub repository.  While it seems natural to download the starting material and jump right into the work, resist this urge and be very intentional about utilizing the features of Git.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you begin a challenge, you should create a GitHub repository and do all of your work step by step capturing your work as you go.    </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you are ready to try that, go to<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-capture-a-tutorial-project-in-a-github-repository/\"> the challenge page</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you are all finished with the challenge, take the time to update the ReadMe file in the repository.   In the first paragraph, and prominently marked, describe the specific skills demonstrated.  For instance if you are learning new HTML5 multimedia tags, list those.   This will be important when you start looking for work.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, update your resumé, CV, or Upwork profile to have a link to that repository.  A prospect client reading your profile will be able to click on that and see a clear demonstration that you actually do know that specific skill.    One final note is that when you do a real project of your own design,  replace the link to the challenge repository with a link to your own original project repository.   Putting your skills to work on a project of your own design shows that you really know how and why to use that skill.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Create a project with other developers.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you learn with your friends take the opportunity to propose an original project that you all can work on together.   Get a consensus of the scope and focus of the project, but feel free to include some features that require a skill that only a few collaborators know well.   This teaches the real world reality that open-source software is a collaboration of many people to build and enhance projects that no single person can achieve alone. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Search GitHub for a project that you are interested in learning more about it. </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Take some time to browse the galaxy of open-source projects in GitHub and find ones that you know about, or are interested in learning about.   You can actively follow the work of others, and can review the code that has been pushed to see how it has been coded.    Clone the repository to your local machine so you have a working copy.  As you test it out and find bugs or desired features, consider creating an issue in the GitHub project.   Note that some repositories have restrictions about who can do what.   By following projects, you will learn.  As you submit features, and if you get a chance to fix an issue you will start building your public credentials.   When you do that, be sure to update your resumé or CV or profile to point the projects you have participated in.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Work globally','','inherit','closed','closed','','59-revision-v1','','','2024-02-16 17:10:47','2024-02-16 17:10:47','',59,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=225',0,'revision','',0),(226,1,'2024-02-16 17:14:24','2024-02-16 17:14:24','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have read some of this site it is good to put some of that to a test with a challenge.    There are often several paths that will get you to one of these challenges.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you complete a challenge tell me what you learned and what questions you still have.   For now, we can do that through email and later we can get more formal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, dive in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-yourself-so-i-know-how-i-can-help-you/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"181\"><strong>Tell me about yourself </strong>so I know how I can help you.</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-your-development-setup/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"184\"><strong>Tell me about your development setup</strong>,</a> what you already can do, and what you want to be able to do.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-setup-your-own-github-account-and-install-desktop-github-app/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"187\">Setup your own GitHub account and install Desktop GitHub app.</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-capture-a-tutorial-project-in-a-github-repository/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"222\">Take any development challenge and record your work in a GitHub repository.</a> </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lots more to come... </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Take a challenge','','inherit','closed','closed','','178-revision-v1','','','2024-02-16 17:14:24','2024-02-16 17:14:24','',178,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=226',0,'revision','',0),(227,1,'2024-02-16 17:16:02','2024-02-16 17:16:02','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Basic necessities in a development platform:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Computer</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Internet access</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Web browser</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>File management - either GUI and/or command line commands.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Text editor</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Source management and distribution system</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Collaboration applications</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While those are the basics, you will likely also need:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Web hosting service</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Interactive Development Environment (IDE)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Remote development shell</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Common platforms:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I\'ll not bother to describe all the many programs needed for each of these platforms since that will be found in the Development Tools page.   Rather, I\'ll discuss some of the unique attributes of each and how they relate.   You have probably already chosen a favorite platform, but may also be considering some alternatives.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Linux</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Almost all web hosting servers are running Linux so ultimately if you are going to do full stack development you will need to learn Linux.   Many developers have chosen to also use Linux as their local work computer.  We will discuss hosting servers a little later on this page, but for now we will consider Linux as a local development computer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Linux of course can be installed on PC\'s and Macintoshes.   It can be installed in a virtual machine on either of those platforms.   It also can run native on Windows using <a href=\"https://cygwin.com\">Cygwin</a> which gives an existing Windows user the ability to use both Windows apps and Linux apps interchangeably.   That also eases the Linux learning curve.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>MacOS is based on Unix and the Mac Terminal app depends on Unix (Linux) shells for line mode interactive commands.   There are many different shells available to choose from, but the most commonly used one in my experience is BASH.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you choose to run Linux as your native OS then you will almost always a graphical user interface.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Windows</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With Windows you naturally have a graphical interface include Windows Explorer,  a web browser like Edge, an interactive command line tool like PowerShell or cmd.exe.   Using your browser there are applications galore that you can download and install.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition as mentioned above you can also install <a href=\"https://cygwin.com\">Cygwin</a> and get lots of Linux goodies as well.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Macintosh</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As mentioned above MacOS is really UNIX under the covers.   The Terminal window runs many different UNIX shells.   Many common development tools are available for download and install and ready for use.     </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, since Terminal gets you into the core of UNIX there are many UNIX, and Linux package managers available that will let you install just like you are in Linux.  Homebrew is one option.   Just Google \'<a href=\"https://duckduckgo.com/?hps=1&amp;q=package+managers+for+mac&amp;ia=web\">package managers for mac</a>\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Web hosting servers</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Most servers are virtual machines in a cloud server farms.   These are almost always headless meaning there is no display and keyboard.   You must access  these using some form of secure shell.   Checkout a google of \'<a href=\"https://duckduckgo.com/?q=ssh&amp;t=osx&amp;ia=web\">ssh</a>\'.   ssh and many programs that use it require secure certificates to be generated and installed on your local machine.  I will have a whole \'How to\' page dedicated to secure networking. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">How about you? </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Give all of those options you probably already have a development platform of some sort and it\'s now time to talk about it.     I need to know about your setup, your needs, and your questions.    I have a \'<a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-your-development-setup/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"184\">Tell me about your development setup</a>\' challenge page that you can use to tell me all about it.   So, go there and tell me.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Development platforms','','inherit','closed','closed','','175-revision-v1','','','2024-02-16 17:16:02','2024-02-16 17:16:02','',175,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=227',0,'revision','',0),(228,1,'2024-02-16 17:16:44','2024-02-16 17:16:44','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have read some of this site it is good to put some of that to a test with a challenge.    There are often several paths that will get you to one of these challenges.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you complete a challenge tell me what you learned and what questions you still have.   For now, we can do that through email and later we can get more formal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, dive in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-yourself-so-i-know-how-i-can-help-you/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"181\"><strong>Tell me about yourself </strong>so I know how I can help you.</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-tell-me-about-your-development-setup/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"184\"><strong>Tell me about your development setup</strong>,</a> what you already can do, and what you want to be able to do.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-setup-your-own-github-account-and-install-desktop-github-app/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"187\"><strong>Setup your own GitHub account</strong> and install Desktop GitHub app.</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/challenge-capture-a-tutorial-project-in-a-github-repository/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"222\"><strong>Take any development challenge </strong>and record your work in a GitHub repository.</a> </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lots more to come... </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Take a challenge','','inherit','closed','closed','','178-revision-v1','','','2024-02-16 17:16:44','2024-02-16 17:16:44','',178,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=228',0,'revision','',0),(229,1,'2024-02-17 21:28:29','2024-02-17 21:28:29','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The initial construction process is complete enough that I\'m ready for a soft opening.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I welcome visitors and would greatly appreciate feedback.  After you have looked around a bit and think this might be helpful to you, please let me know.  On posts like this you can simply leave a comment.  It should also give you the option to subscribe when you submit the comment.  You can also subscribe on the bottom of the side bar.  Lastly you can simply email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you get far enough to find one of my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenges </a> please engage and let me know how it goes for you.   Each challenge should include a request to send me a detailed email, and I would greatly appreciate it if you do so.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I still have a lot of writing to do so please check back often.   My writing will be prioritized around what you find valuable.  I\'m happy to revise any of it to make it more valuable to you. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, for now, have a look around. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Welcome to my mentoring site!','','publish','open','open','','welcome-to-my-mentoring-site','','','2024-03-09 15:31:42','2024-03-09 15:31:42','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=229',0,'post','',5),(230,1,'2024-02-17 21:28:29','2024-02-17 21:28:29','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The initial construction process is complete enough that I\'m ready for a soft opening.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I welcome visitors and would greatly appreciate feedback.  So, please leave a comment on this post to let me know you have stopped by.  After you have looked around a bit and think this might be helpful to you, please let me know.  You can do so either in your comment or by a private email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you get far enough to find one of my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenges </a> please engage and let me know how it goes for you.   Each challenge should include a request to send me a detailed email, and I would greatly appreciate it if you do so.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I still have a lot of writing to do so please check back often.   My writing will prioritized around what you find valuable.  I\'m happy to revise any of it to make it more valuable to you. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, for now, have a look around. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Welcome to my mentoring site!','','inherit','closed','closed','','229-revision-v1','','','2024-02-17 21:28:29','2024-02-17 21:28:29','',229,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=230',0,'revision','',0),(232,1,'2024-02-17 21:50:18','2024-02-17 21:50:18','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The initial construction process is complete enough that I\'m ready for a soft opening.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I welcome visitors and would greatly appreciate feedback.  After you have looked around a bit and think this might be helpful to you, please let me know.  I have not figured out the best way to handle subscriptions and memberships, so in the mean time please send an email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you get far enough to find one of my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenges </a> please engage and let me know how it goes for you.   Each challenge should include a request to send me a detailed email, and I would greatly appreciate it if you do so.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I still have a lot of writing to do so please check back often.   My writing will prioritized around what you find valuable.  I\'m happy to revise any of it to make it more valuable to you. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, for now, have a look around. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Welcome to my mentoring site!','','inherit','closed','closed','','229-revision-v1','','','2024-02-17 21:50:18','2024-02-17 21:50:18','',229,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=232',0,'revision','',0),(239,1,'2024-02-19 14:06:13','2024-02-19 14:06:13','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because of the rapid pace of technology development and market requirements, most web and application development is done by integrated teams.  No one person can do it all themselves. It takes a team of specialists working individually and cross discipline to be successful. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Some of the roles that are needed are:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Project lead</strong> - responsible for planning how the individuals in the team can work together to complete the project.   This is usually done in cooperation with the whole team to come to consensus on next steps and how to keep the project moving.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Design lead</strong> - responsible for the technical design and requirements for each major piece of the solution.   This person is responsible for making sure that the contribution of all the team members will fit together and produce a good product.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Database designer</strong> - much of the interface between the different parts of the solution are stored in a database.   This person designs the specific tables, columns, and indexes needed to ensure proper communication and integrity.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Lead coder</strong> - this coder is the lead and will establish and enforce coding standards and facilitate code reviews.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Coder</strong> - an individual contributor that writes one or more specific code components. They may be front end, back end, or full stack coders depending on the languages they are proficient in. They will also design and write functional tests that ensure proper operation. These tests are often referred to as <strong>unit tests</strong> because they test the function of a specific code module.    </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Tester</strong> - a person responsible for designing an implementing test suites that ensure that the individual code components operate together.   This person will often work with the individual coders to ensure their unit tests are properly written.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Documenter</strong> - works with the individual team members to understand how their contributions work and writes functional internal documentation and/or end user documentation.  The documentation may be in the form of a user manual but will also likely have on screen components such as roll-over tool tips or info links like ⓘ.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Source controller</strong> - ensures that all of the artifacts of the team members are properly kept in a repository and that all changes to those artifacts are also captured in the repository.  </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_engineering\">Software engineering</a> team processes</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Requirements_analysis\">Requirements analysis</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Scope and effort estimation</strong> </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Prioritizing next steps and coordinating cadence and milestones</strong> - eg. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agile_software_development\">Agile</a> </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_review\">Code reviews</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integration_testing\">Integration testing</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_integration\">Continuous integration</a></strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_deployment\">Software deployment</a></strong> - </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_tool\">Team tools</a></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The team processes are often facilitated by specialized software.  Here is a list of some of those.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repository_(version_control)\"><strong>Project repository manager</strong></a> - eg. GitHub</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_reviewing_software\"><strong>Code review software</strong></a> - eg. <a href=\"https://www.gerritcodereview.com/index.html\">Gerrit</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Bug, feature, and project management system</strong> - eg. <a href=\"https://www.atlassian.com/software/jira\">Jira</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_unit_testing_frameworks\"><strong>Unit testing framework</strong></a> - eg. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Source, build, testing and deployment automation system</strong> - eg. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jenkins_(software)\">Jenkins</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_integration\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><strong>Continuous integration system</strong></a> - eg. GitHub Actions</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Deployment framework</strong> - eg. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kubernetes\">Kubernetes</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Build your brand</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The best way to build your skills as a team player and move up to more responsible positions is to find a role that you can already fill and join a team.   With a little effort you will be able to learn more about the other team members and their roles as well as learn more about the larger project.   As you develop your skills you can build a reputation of trust.   Open source software projects are a great opportunity because they depend on volunteer contributions.  But, it should be noted that all work done for open software projects is not done for free.  The companies or organizations that rely on open source software often have specific needs that are not necessarily shared by the community at large.   These organizations will often pay their employees, or outside developers, to work on their special needs.  A close friend of mine does exactly this at SAS where I retired from. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many open source projects are dependent on other open source projects.  Working on one can give you valuable skills and understanding that can be a gateway to other projects.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, you can build relationships with other developers and learn of other opportunities.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Working in a team','','inherit','closed','closed','','149-revision-v1','','','2024-02-19 14:06:13','2024-02-19 14:06:13','',149,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=239',0,'revision','',0),(245,1,'2024-02-19 20:10:49','2024-02-19 20:10:49','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The initial construction process is complete enough that I\'m ready for a soft opening.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I welcome visitors and would greatly appreciate feedback.  After you have looked around a bit and think this might be helpful to you, please let me know.  On posts like this you can simply leave a comment.  It should also give you the option to subscribe when you submit the comment.  You can also subscribe on the bottom of the side bar.  Lastly you can simply email to <a href=\"mailto:MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com\">MichaelKentBurns@gmail.com</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you get far enough to find one of my <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenges </a> please engage and let me know how it goes for you.   Each challenge should include a request to send me a detailed email, and I would greatly appreciate it if you do so.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I still have a lot of writing to do so please check back often.   My writing will prioritized around what you find valuable.  I\'m happy to revise any of it to make it more valuable to you. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So, for now, have a look around. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Welcome to my mentoring site!','','inherit','closed','closed','','229-revision-v1','','','2024-02-19 20:10:49','2024-02-19 20:10:49','',229,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=245',0,'revision','',0),(247,1,'2024-02-24 13:17:16','2024-02-24 13:17:16','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Running a hosted WordPress site on a cloud service is made possible by a number of services.   I use Cloudways, but there are others such as WPEngine.   In order to do development in those environments a developer needs to know Linux, shell, and remote headless environments including secure shell access.   The software that must be installed on a remote server is frequently referred to as LAMP, which stands for <strong>L</strong>inux Apache MySQL, PHP.    Typically, LAMP is installed as a series of servers which much be installed and configured on a Linux machine.  That is a fairly complex setup beyond the beginner Web developer. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is also a Macintosh equivalent called <strong>M</strong>AMP where <strong>M</strong> stands for Macintosh rather than Linux.   MAMP is neatly packaged up as a single downloadable application.   When you run the MAMP application it presents a simple control panel that allows you to start, stop, and monitor all of the various servers that are built into the application.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, for developers without those skills there are also several open source solutions that allow you to run a full stack environment on a Mac, Linux, or Windows personal computer.   One that I choose is called XAMPP.   The \'<strong>X</strong>\'  means that it will run on Linux, Windows, or Macintosh.      The one great simplification is that it is all packaged up as a single application like MAMP is. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"flexWrap\":\"nowrap\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org/download.html\">XAMPP</a> is available from an open source software group named <a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org\">Apache Friends</a>.   There are download links there for Windows, Linux, and OS X (Macintosh OS).    Each of those are simple application download and installs.    If you can download and install an app on your machine, you can download and install a complete full stack! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":254,\"width\":\"128px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/XAMPP-icon.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-254\" style=\"width:128px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The name <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XAMPP\">XAMPP</a> means that it includes these technologies built in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>X</strong> - Can be installed on Windows, Macintosh, or Linux</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A</strong> - <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_HTTP_Server\">Apache web server</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>M<strong> </strong>- <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MySQL\">MySQL</a> database</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>P</strong> - <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PHP\">PHP</a> programming language built into the web stack</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>P</strong> - <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl\">Perl</a> is a highly portable and very versatile programming language and library</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the <a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org/\">Apache Friends</a> page there is a short and well done video showing the installation and startup of XAMPP on Windows.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once it is installed it is configured to run.   On Windows a new XAMPP application is added to the Start Menu.  Once it is started you can start and stop all the components of the stack, administer their details, see the error logs and more.   There are also buttons to get to Windows Explorer, a shell, the services menu, and more.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once Apache and MySQL services are started you can point your browser to the URL <a href=\"http://localhost\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">http://localhost</a> and be greeted by the XAMPP welcome page.   At the top of that page there is a dark blue menu bar.   There you will find links to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Apache Friends</strong> - The organization that supports XAMPP</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FAQs</strong> - obvious</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>HOW-TO Guides</strong> - how to do many XAMPP tasks</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>PHPInfo</strong> - an extensive report of the live status of all the components of your PHP installation.  This includes lots of details you may need to know when developing and debugging your stack and any web pages that you will host in XAMPP.  You don\'t need to try to learn about all those details, thankfully.   In the upper right of the page is a \'php\' logo which leads to its extensive documentation. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>phpMyAdmin</strong> - a very helpful control panel for your MySQL database and other PHP details.  On that page, under the \'phpMyAdmin\' title of the sidebar, there is a question mark icon that leads to the documentation for this control panel.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Finally, you can add things to this menu, but that is a lesson for another day</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have read this and followed the directions to do the install, then congratulations are in order because you now are hosting a full stack web server on your personal computer.   You have completed another <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenge</a> from the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenge list</a>.   If you have not done so while reading this page, consider taking the time to do that now. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other how-to pages will guide you through processes like installing your own Wordpress server, learning how to debug it and much more.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Using XAMPP for development work','','publish','closed','closed','','using-xampp-for-development-work','','','2024-02-27 00:31:05','2024-02-27 00:31:05','',0,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?page_id=247',0,'page','',0),(248,1,'2024-02-24 13:17:16','2024-02-24 13:17:16','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Running a hosted WordPress site on a cloud service is made possible by a number of services.   I use Cloudways, but there are others such as WPEngine.   In order to do development in those environments a developer needs to know Linux, shell, and remote headless environments including secure shell access.   The software that must be installed on a remote server is frequently referred to as LAMP, which stands for <strong>L</strong>inux Apache MySQL, PHP.    Typically, LAMP is installed as a series of servers which much be installed and configured on a Linux machine.  That is a fairly complex setup beyond the beginner Web developer. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is also a Macintosh equivalent called <strong>M</strong>AMP where <strong>M</strong> stands for Macintosh rather than Linux.   MAMP is neatly packaged up as a single downloadable application.   When you run the MAMP application it presents a simple control panel that allows you to start, stop, and monitor all of the various servers that are built into the application.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, for developers without those skills there are also several open source solutions that allow you to run a full stack environment on a Mac, Linux, or Windows personal computer.   One that I choose is called XAMPP.   The \'<strong>X</strong>\'  means that it will run on Linux, Windows, or Macintosh.      The one great simplification is that it is all packaged up as a single application like MAMP is. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org/download.html\">XAMPP</a> is available from an open software group named <a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org\">Apache Friends</a>.   There are download links there for Windows, Linux, and OS X (Macintosh OS).    Each of those are simple application download and installs.    If you can download and install an app on your machine, you can download and install a complete full stack! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Using XAMPP for development work','','inherit','closed','closed','','247-revision-v1','','','2024-02-24 13:17:16','2024-02-24 13:17:16','',247,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=248',0,'revision','',0),(249,1,'2024-02-24 13:18:41','2024-02-24 13:18:41','<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to/how-to-contribute-to-this-site/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"115\">Contribute to this site</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to-administer-a-wordpress-site/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to-administer-a-wordpress-site/\">WordPress administrative tasks</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cloudways hosting administration tasks:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Find your way around this site:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Install a full stack on your local development computer</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','How to ...','','inherit','closed','closed','','108-autosave-v1','','','2024-02-24 13:18:41','2024-02-24 13:18:41','',108,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=249',0,'revision','',0),(250,1,'2024-02-24 13:18:53','2024-02-24 13:18:53','<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to/how-to-contribute-to-this-site/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"115\">Contribute to this site</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to-administer-a-wordpress-site/\" data-type=\"link\" data-id=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/how-to-administer-a-wordpress-site/\">WordPress administrative tasks</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cloudways hosting administration tasks:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Find your way around this site:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/using-xampp-for-development-work/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"247\">Install a full stack on your local development computer</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','How to ...','','inherit','closed','closed','','108-revision-v1','','','2024-02-24 13:18:53','2024-02-24 13:18:53','',108,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=250',0,'revision','',0),(252,1,'2024-02-24 13:23:09','2024-02-24 13:23:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Running a hosted WordPress site on a cloud service is made possible by a number of services.   I use Cloudways, but there are others such as WPEngine.   In order to do development in those environments a developer needs to know Linux, shell, and remote headless environments including secure shell access.   The software that must be installed on a remote server is frequently referred to as LAMP, which stands for <strong>L</strong>inux Apache MySQL, PHP.    Typically, LAMP is installed as a series of servers which much be installed and configured on a Linux machine.  That is a fairly complex setup beyond the beginner Web developer. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is also a Macintosh equivalent called <strong>M</strong>AMP where <strong>M</strong> stands for Macintosh rather than Linux.   MAMP is neatly packaged up as a single downloadable application.   When you run the MAMP application it presents a simple control panel that allows you to start, stop, and monitor all of the various servers that are built into the application.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, for developers without those skills there are also several open source solutions that allow you to run a full stack environment on a Mac, Linux, or Windows personal computer.   One that I choose is called XAMPP.   The \'<strong>X</strong>\'  means that it will run on Linux, Windows, or Macintosh.      The one great simplification is that it is all packaged up as a single application like MAMP is. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org/download.html\">XAMPP</a> is available from an open software group named <a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org\">Apache Friends</a>.   There are download links there for Windows, Linux, and OS X (Macintosh OS).    Each of those are simple application download and installs.    If you can download and install an app on your machine, you can download and install a complete full stack! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the <a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org/\">Apache Friends</a> page there is a short and well done video showing the installation and startup of XAMPP on Windows.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Using XAMPP for development work','','inherit','closed','closed','','247-revision-v1','','','2024-02-24 13:23:09','2024-02-24 13:23:09','',247,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=252',0,'revision','',0),(254,1,'2024-02-26 16:31:57','2024-02-26 16:31:57','','XAMPP-icon','','inherit','open','closed','','xampp-icon','','','2024-02-26 16:31:57','2024-02-26 16:31:57','',247,'https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/XAMPP-icon.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(255,1,'2024-02-26 17:11:40','2024-02-26 17:11:40','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Running a hosted WordPress site on a cloud service is made possible by a number of services.   I use Cloudways, but there are others such as WPEngine.   In order to do development in those environments a developer needs to know Linux, shell, and remote headless environments including secure shell access.   The software that must be installed on a remote server is frequently referred to as LAMP, which stands for <strong>L</strong>inux Apache MySQL, PHP.    Typically, LAMP is installed as a series of servers which much be installed and configured on a Linux machine.  That is a fairly complex setup beyond the beginner Web developer. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is also a Macintosh equivalent called <strong>M</strong>AMP where <strong>M</strong> stands for Macintosh rather than Linux.   MAMP is neatly packaged up as a single downloadable application.   When you run the MAMP application it presents a simple control panel that allows you to start, stop, and monitor all of the various servers that are built into the application.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, for developers without those skills there are also several open source solutions that allow you to run a full stack environment on a Mac, Linux, or Windows personal computer.   One that I choose is called XAMPP.   The \'<strong>X</strong>\'  means that it will run on Linux, Windows, or Macintosh.      The one great simplification is that it is all packaged up as a single application like MAMP is. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"flexWrap\":\"nowrap\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org/download.html\">XAMPP</a> is available from an open software group named <a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org\">Apache Friends</a>.   There are download links there for Windows, Linux, and OS X (Macintosh OS).    Each of those are simple application download and installs.    If you can download and install an app on your machine, you can download and install a complete full stack! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":254,\"width\":\"128px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img src=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/XAMPP-icon.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-254\" style=\"width:128px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The name <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XAMPP\">XAMPP</a> means that it includes these technologies built in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>X</strong> - Can be installed on Windows, Macintosh, or Linux</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>A</strong> - <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_HTTP_Server\">Apache web server</a></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>M<strong> </strong>- <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MySQL\">MySQL</a> database</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>P</strong> - <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PHP\">PHP</a> programming language built into the web stack</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>P</strong> - <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl\">Perl</a> is a highly portable and very versatile programming language and library</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the <a href=\"https://www.apachefriends.org/\">Apache Friends</a> page there is a short and well done video showing the installation and startup of XAMPP on Windows.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once it is installed it is configured to run.   On Windows a new XAMPP application is added to the Start Menu.  Once it is started you can start and stop all the components of the stack, administer their details, see the error logs and more.   There are also buttons to get to Windows Explorer, a shell, the services menu, and more.  </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once Apache and MySQL services are started you can point your browser to the URL <a href=\"http://localhost\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">http://localhost</a> and be greeted by the XAMPP welcome page.   At the top of that page there is a dark blue menu bar.   There you will find links to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Apache Friends</strong> - The organization that supports XAMPP</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>FAQs</strong> - obvious</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>HOW-TO Guides</strong> - how to do many XAMPP tasks</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>PHPInfo</strong> - an extensive report of the live status of all the components of your PHP installation.  This includes lots of details you may need to know when developing and debugging your stack and any web pages that you will host in XAMPP.  You don\'t need to try to learn about all those details, thankfully.   In the upper right of the page is a \'php\' logo which leads to its extensive documentation. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>phpMyAdmin</strong> - a very helpful control panel for your MySQL database and other PHP details.  On that page, under the \'phpMyAdmin\' title of the sidebar, there is a question mark icon that leads to the documentation for this control panel.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Finally, you can add things to this menu, but that is a lesson for another day</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have read this and followed the directions to do the install, then congratulations are in order because you now are hosting a full stack web server on your personal computer.   You have completed another <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenge</a> from the <a href=\"https://michaelkentburns.com/index.php/take-a-challenge/\" data-type=\"page\" data-id=\"178\">challenge list</a>.   If you have not done so while reading this page, consider taking the time to do that now. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Other how-to pages will guide you through processes like install your own Wordpress server, learning how to debug it and much more.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Using XAMPP for development work','','inherit','closed','closed','','247-revision-v1','','','2024-02-26 17:11:40','2024-02-26 17:11:40','',247,'https://michaelkentburns.com/?p=255',0,'revision','',0),(256,1,'2024-02-27 00:27:53','2024-02-27 00:27:53','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Running a hosted WordPress site on a cloud service is made possible by a number of services.   I use Cloudways, but there are others such as WPEngine.   In order to do development in those environments a developer needs to know Linux, shell, and remote headless environments including secure shell access.   The software that must be installed on a remote server is frequently referred to as LAMP, which stands for <strong>L</strong>inux Apache MySQL, PHP.    Typically, LAMP is installed as a series of servers which much be installed and configured on a Linux machine.  That is a fairly complex setup beyond the beginner Web developer. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is also a Macintosh equivalent called <strong>M</strong>AMP where <strong>M</strong> stands for Macintosh rather than Linux.   MAMP is neatly packaged up as a single downloadable application.   When you run the MAMP application it presents a simple control panel that allows you to start, stop, and monitor all of the various servers that are built into the application.   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, for developers without those skills there are also several open source solutions that allow you to run a full stack environment on a Mac, Linux, or Windows personal computer.   One that I choose is called XAMPP.   The \'<strong>X</strong>\'  means that it will run on Linux, Windows,